They are 3 times as likely to consider abortion murder as opposed to baptist or catholic men (56% vs 27%, respectively.).

So what gives? Shouldn’t they be more willing to accept the right of one woman to control her own body than some larger percentage?

But my data doesn’t match my image of Jehovah’s Witnesses. They are the Sectarians who don’t believe in socialised medicine which includes what I believe to be the responsibility of government to help make sure women have real access to choice about whether they’re pregnant.

Assuming a fall rate of about 5%, Jehovah’s Witnesses in Namibia change their mind about 1/2 the time and either have the child or, in some cases, re-impregnate. All other Namibians were aborting down at 9% although actually having the child rather than aborting down at 12%.

Namibians, including Jehovah’s Witnesses, are dithering about their place in the universe whether it is about God taking away their reproductive rights or pouring cold water over their microaggressive comments about “just trying to be friendly” to women of colour.

It is about being who you say you are. Which is what the Who we are campaign from Amnesty International is about.
